{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":21793,"record_hash":"sha256:8e3b718cd162fbe88d6ace34aae9d8379fd8db028bed8f378c9b1a08882143c6","timestamp":"2026-05-10T21:13:39.021Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 5d8753\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1020\nOutput:\n\t\"source_key\": \"sha256-...\",\n\t\"record_index\": 0,\n\t\"record_hash\": \"sha256:...\",\n\t\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-07T09:08:43.427Z\",\n\t\"event_kind\": \"response_item\",\n\t\"role\": \"assistant\",\n\t\"content_text\": \"redacted normalized text when easy to extract\",\n\t\"tool_name\": null,\n\t\"source_record\": {}\n}\n```\n\nSlim normalized fields support timeline browsing and handoff without reparsing\nevery provider-specific record:\n\n- `event_kind`: provider event type, with a nested event type when obvious\n- `role` and `content_text`: conversation body when extraction is obvious\n- `tool_name`: obvious tool activity\n- `source_record`: redacted provider record for provenance and future adapters\n\nOmit repeated session/source metadata from each transcript record. Also omit git\nbranch, provider session ids, message ids, parent ids, and turn ids from\ntop-level record fields.\n\nRecord hashes and dedupe use the original trimmed JSONL bytes, not the redacted\ntranscript record.\n\n## Deduplication\n\nUse stable record hashes:\n\n```text\nsha256(trimmed raw JSONL line bytes)\n```\n\nTranscript append dedupe is rebuilt from the stored transcript list by reading\neach record's `record_hash`. Re-running capture against the same transcript is a\nno-op unless the transcript grew.\n\n## Future Association Model\n\nDo not attach transcript data directly to branches, commits, changes, or pull\nrequests in the POC. The project session is the durable object.\n\nLater, when GitButler has an explicit target, write relationship references:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/commit target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nSee [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md) for access patterns and product\nmotivation.\n\n## Publication\n\nThe POC writes shareable-ready keys but does not publish them. GitMeta\nserialization, push, fetch, and sync require a later privacy and product\ndecision.\n- follow-up questions\n\nThis helps reviewers understand whether the generated work was carefully guide\n[TRUNCATED]\ny later ask a follow-up question against that session context,\nfor example whether a payments edge case was considered.\n\nThe POC only captures redacted session records. It does not create web links,\npublish metadata, or attach sessions to pull requests.\n\nExpected access pattern:\n\n1. start from a pull request, branch, change, or commit\n2. read its future `gitbutler:agent-sessions` relationship set\n3. resolve those session keys on the `project` target\n4. render each session's transcript timeline from the slim transcript records\n5. use redacted `source_record` for provenance and later normalization upgrades\n\nThat means branch/PR metadata should point to sessions, not contain copies of\nsession transcripts.\n\n## Many-to-Many Relationships\n\nSessions and code review objects are not one-to-one.\n\nOne branch or pull request may involve multiple sessions:\n\n```text\nPR A\n  -> session 1\n  -> session 2\n```\n\nOne session may also contribute to multiple branches or pull requests, especially\nin GitButler where a worktree can contain several active branches and a user may\ncommit different hunks to different destinations:\n\n```text\nsession 1\n  -> feature branch\n  -> bugfix branch\n```\n\nThe durable object should therefore be the project-scoped GitButler agent\nsession. Branches, commits, changes, and pull requests should later reference\nsession keys rather than own the transcript data directly.\n\nThis is especially important for GitButler because a single worktree may contain\nmultiple active branches at once. An agent can produce edits that the user later\nsplits across several branches, so the capture layer should not guess ownership\nfrom the current branch.\n\nFuture relationship keys can look like this:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/commit target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nThat shape supports:\n\n- sessions that exist before code is written\n- one session associated with many branch or review objects\n- many sessions associated with one branch or review object\n- branch or commit associations being added after capture\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T21:13:39.021Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}